# React Native Component Standards

These rules apply to reusable UI building blocks in `src/components/`.

## Component Shape

Components must be **functional components** written as **named arrow functions** with an **explicit return type**.

- Use `React.JSX.Element` (or `React.ReactElement`) as the return type.
- Define a dedicated `Props` interface (or type alias) for every component that accepts props.
- Export the component as the default export or a named export — never as an anonymous default.
- Class components are forbidden.

```typescript
// BAD — no return type, inline props, anonymous default
export default ({ title }: { title: string }) => {
  return <Text>{title}</Text>;
};

// BAD — class component
export class PrimaryButton extends React.Component {
  render() {
    return <Pressable />;
  }
}

// GOOD — explicit typing, named arrow function
import React from "react";
import { Pressable, Text, StyleSheet } from "react-native";

interface PrimaryButtonProps {
  label: string;
  onPress: () => void;
  disabled?: boolean;
}

const PrimaryButton = ({
  label,
  onPress,
  disabled = false,
}: PrimaryButtonProps): React.JSX.Element => {
  return (
    <Pressable onPress={onPress} disabled={disabled} style={styles.button}>
      <Text style={styles.label}>{label}</Text>
    </Pressable>
  );
};

const styles = StyleSheet.create({
  button: { paddingVertical: 12, paddingHorizontal: 24, borderRadius: 8 },
  label: { fontSize: 16, fontWeight: "600" },
});

export default PrimaryButton;
```

## Safe Area Layout

The application root wraps the tree in `SafeAreaProvider` (see `src/App.tsx`). Components that render edge-to-edge content must respect device insets.

- Use `useSafeAreaInsets()` from `react-native-safe-area-context` for custom padding on headers, footers, and floating elements.
- Use `SafeAreaView` from `react-native-safe-area-context` (not the deprecated RN core export) for full-screen containers.
- Never hardcode notch, status bar, or home-indicator offsets (e.g., `paddingTop: 44`).

```typescript
// BAD — magic number for notch clearance
const ScreenHeader = (): React.JSX.Element => (
  <View style={{ paddingTop: 44 }}>
    <Text>Title</Text>
  </View>
);

// GOOD — dynamic insets from the provider
import { useSafeAreaInsets } from "react-native-safe-area-context";

interface ScreenHeaderProps {
  title: string;
}

const ScreenHeader = ({ title }: ScreenHeaderProps): React.JSX.Element => {
  const insets = useSafeAreaInsets();

  return (
    <View style={{ paddingTop: insets.top, paddingHorizontal: 16 }}>
      <Text>{title}</Text>
    </View>
  );
};
```

Provider order at the app root must remain: `SafeAreaProvider` → `ThemeProvider` → `NavigationContainer`.

## Performance — Memoization Requirements

Apply memoization where re-renders carry measurable cost.

- Wrap **list item components** in `React.memo`.
- Use `useMemo` for expensive derived values (filtered lists, computed totals, merged styles from theme tokens).
- Use `useCallback` for handlers passed to memoized children, `FlatList`/`SectionList` `renderItem`, or `keyExtractor`.
- Do not pass inline object or array literals as props to memoized children — they defeat referential equality.

```typescript
// BAD — new function and object on every parent render
const ParentList = ({ items }: ParentListProps): React.JSX.Element => {
  return (
    <FlatList
      data={items}
      renderItem={({ item }) => <ItemRow item={item} onPress={() => handlePress(item.id)} />}
      contentContainerStyle={{ padding: 16 }}
    />
  );
};

// GOOD — stable callbacks and memoized child
const ItemRow = React.memo(({ item, onPress }: ItemRowProps): React.JSX.Element => (
  <Pressable onPress={onPress}>
    <Text>{item.title}</Text>
  </Pressable>
));

const ParentList = ({ items }: ParentListProps): React.JSX.Element => {
  const handlePress = useCallback((id: string) => {
    // navigate or dispatch
  }, []);

  const renderItem = useCallback(
    ({ item }: ListRenderItemInfo<Item>) => (
      <ItemRow item={item} onPress={() => handlePress(item.id)} />
    ),
    [handlePress],
  );

  const contentStyle = useMemo(() => ({ padding: 16 }), []);

  return (
    <FlatList
      data={items}
      renderItem={renderItem}
      keyExtractor={(item) => item.id}
      contentContainerStyle={contentStyle}
    />
  );
};
```

## Props Typing — Good vs Bad

```typescript
// BAD — untyped rest spread, optional props without defaults documented
const Avatar = (props) => {
  const { uri, size } = props;
  return <Image source={{ uri }} style={{ width: size, height: size }} />;
};

// BAD — React.FC without explicit Props interface
const Avatar: React.FC = ({ uri, size = 40 }) => { /* ... */ };

// GOOD — dedicated interface, explicit return type, typed StyleSheet
import type { ImageSourcePropType, ImageStyle } from "react-native";

interface AvatarProps {
  uri: string;
  size?: number;
  style?: ImageStyle;
}

const Avatar = ({
  uri,
  size = 40,
  style,
}: AvatarProps): React.JSX.Element => {
  const source: ImageSourcePropType = { uri };

  return (
    <Image
      source={source}
      style={[styles.base, { width: size, height: size }, style]}
    />
  );
};

const styles = StyleSheet.create({
  base: { borderRadius: 999 },
});
```

## Styling Conventions

- NativeWind utility classes are available project-wide via `global.css` imported in `src/App.tsx`.
- `StyleSheet.create` is acceptable and preferred for complex or theme-driven styles.
- Pull all color, spacing, typography, and radius tokens from `useTheme()` or `useThemeContext()` using the **Midnight Edge** design system in `src/config/theme.ts` — use `toTextStyle()` for typography. Do not hardcode hex values or font sizes. See `theme-colors-and-depth.mdc`, `theme-typography-and-layout.mdc`, and `theme-component-and-motion.mdc`.
- Style props must be typed (`ViewStyle`, `TextStyle`, `ImageStyle`) — never untyped style objects.
